purpose:
  This system exists to make a person's ideas, tasks, notes, and reminders
  visible, connected, and actionable from a single view.

  It solves the problem of fragmented information — items scattered across
  files with no structure, no relationships, no priority, and no way to
  see the big picture.

  Success means: the user opens the dashboard and knows within seconds
  what matters most, what depends on what, and where to start.

serves:
  1. the individual user — the person capturing and organizing their work
  2. the work itself — ensuring nothing is lost, forgotten, or orphaned
  3. efficiency — always last, never first

values:
  — nothing is ever lost
    no item is permanently deleted. archive, never destroy.
    the user's ideas and work history are preserved indefinitely.

  — capture is frictionless
    the system must never make the user classify or organize
    before they can record a thought. capture first, structure later.

  — relationships are visible
    dependencies, connections, and priorities are not hidden
    in the user's memory. the system makes them explicit and
    displays them clearly.

  — the system is honest about its state
    if something is blocked, overdue, orphaned, or conflicting,
    the system shows it plainly. it does not hide problems.

  — simplicity over feature count
    every feature must earn its place. complexity that does not
    directly serve visibility, capture, or organization is rejected.

boundaries:
  the system will never:
    — permanently delete any user-created content
    — require classification before an item can be saved
    — hide dependency conflicts or circular references
    — send notifications without explicit user configuration
    — share user data with any third party without explicit consent
    — make decisions on behalf of the user without user approval
      (applies to future AI features — suggest, never act)

intent:
  when a situation is ambiguous, ask: does this help the user
  see their work more clearly and decide what to do next?
  if not, the answer is probably no.

  when a feature request conflicts with simplicity, choose
  simplicity unless the user can demonstrate a concrete problem
  the feature solves.

fitness:
  a modification is an improvement if and only if:
    — all spec contracts still hold
    — no user content has been lost or made inaccessible
    — the user can capture, organize, and prioritize
      their work more effectively than before
    — the dashboard provides a clearer view of what matters
    — no boundary has been crossed
